05456nam a22007815i 9780824837709DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248377097 a10.1515/97808248377092doi  a(DE-B1597)484171  a(OCoLC)1013950273  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPN1993.5.C4bZ5 2010eb 7aPOL0330002bisacsh04a792.09512221 aZhang, Yingjin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCinema, Space, and Polylocality in a Globalizing China /cYingjin Zhang. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b34 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Cinema, Space, Polylocality -- t2. Space of Scholarship: Trans/National and Comparative Studies -- t3. Space of Production: Postsocialist Filmmaking -- t4. Space of Polylocality: Remapping the City -- t5. Space of Subjectivity: Independent Documentary -- t6. Space of Performance: Media and Mediation -- t7. Conclusion: Progress, Problems, Prospects -- tNotes -- tFilmography, Videography -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this milestone work, prominent China film scholar Yingjin Zhang proposes "polylocality" as a new conceptual framework for investigating the shifting spaces of contemporary Chinese cinema in the age of globalization. Questioning the national cinema paradigm, Zhang calls for comparative studies of underdeveloped areas beyond the imperative of transnationalism.The book begins by addressing theories and practices related to space, place, and polylocality in contemporary China before focusing on the space of scholarship and urging scholars to move beyond the current paradigm and explore transnational and comparative film studies. This is followed by a chapter that concentrates on the space of production and surveys the changing landscape of postsocialist filmmaking and the transformation of China’s urban generation of directors. Next is an examination of the space of polylocality and the cinematic mappings of Beijing and a persistent "reel" contact with polylocality in hinterland China. In the fifth chapter Zhang explores the space of subjectivity in independent film and video and contextualizes experiments by young directors with various documentary styles. Chapter 6 calls attention to the space of performance and addresses issues of media and mediation by way of two kinds of playing: the first with documentary as troubling information, the second with piracy as creative intervention. The concluding chapter offers an overview of Chinese cinema in the new century and provides production and reception statistics.Combining inspired critical insights, original observations, and new information, Cinema, Space, and Polylocality in a Globalizing China is a significant work on current Chinese film and a must-read for film scholars and anyone seriously interested in cinema more generally or contemporary Chinese culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion pictures and globalizationzChinaxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxProduction and directionzChina. 0aMotion pictureszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszChinaxHistoryy21st century. 0aSpace and time in motion pictures. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package B